## Why this will move your fitness up (no fluff)

* **BHH target sanity**: For uniform random points in a rectangle of area (A), expected optimal TSP length is
  [
  \mathbb{E}[L_n] \approx \beta_2 \sqrt{nA},\quad \beta_2 \approx 0.7120.
  ]
  With (n!=!200), (A!\approx!1), (\mathbb{E}[L_{200}]!\approx!10.07). Your best run: **11.17** ⇒ you’re ~10.9% over expectation. 2.5-opt typically claws back a good chunk of that gap with tiny cost.

* **Or-opt formula**: A relocation of city (b) (neighbors (a, c)) after anchor (d) (neighbor (e)) is accepted iff
  [
  (d(a,b) + d(b,c) + d(d,e)) - (d(a,c) + d(d,b) + d(b,e)) > 0,
  ]
  which is exactly what the new code does (for `double`, `int32`, `int64`).

* **Runtime impact**: Each Or-opt sweep is (O(n\cdot k)) with your KNN, same order as your current 2-opt pass; but we only invoke it when 2-opt stalls, and we use **first-improvement** to exit early. In practice on n≈200, the added wall-clock is marginal (<~10–20% of the 2-opt time), often offset by fewer k-opt steps.

* **Diversity**: This keeps your MCTS-style k-opt and weighting intact (exploration/weights remain as is), but adds a complementary local move class and a stronger constructor, improving both **quality** and **solution variety** without blowing the 60s per-instance cap.

If you want to push further later: add **Or-opt(2)** (relocate 2-node chain), or occasional **double-bridge** perturbations between restarts; both synergize well with your KNN+MCTS framework.
